You can transform raw checkpoint data into a display-friendly format using the `formatCheckpoints` function, as shown in [S1]. This function takes an array of `ThreadState` objects and returns a new array with formatted checkpoint metadata.

Here's an example of how to use this function:
```ts
function formatCheckpoints(history: ThreadState[]) {
  return history.map((cp, index) => ({
    index,
    id: cp.checkpoint?.checkpoint_id,
    taskName: cp.tasks?.[0]?.name ?? "unknown",
    messageCount: (cp.values?.messages as unknown[])?.length ?? 0,
    hasInterrupts: cp.tasks?.some((t) => t.interrupts?.length) ?? false,
    nextNodes: cp.next ?? [],
  }));
}
```
This function is mentioned in [S2] as a way to make it easy to render timeline entries with meaningful labels instead of raw IDs.

Note that this function assumes you have an array of `ThreadState` objects, which are likely retrieved from the LangGraph client using the `getHistory` method, as shown in [S5].

